Extent Unspecified; Bleaching of table Acropora was observed along 2 visual transects (T347 and T 348).
Bleaching extended down to 20 m, but was most extensive in shallow water (almost 100% in some areas, including soft corals and anemones).

than 50% coral mortality. Some areas had coral mortality close to 75%.

SPECIES: Acroporas (at least cerealis and robusta and maybe nana

NOTES: These corals are briefly exposed at low tide (new moon) when we experienced very high atmospheric temperatures coincident with  lack of trade winds.

Bleaching was observed at various spot within the bay.  The mushroom corals were the first to released its symbiont
algae, then some branching Acroporas and certain parts of massive coral heads.

Further bleaching in 2002 that killed many of the remaining non-massive corals. The massive corals also bleached, but
most recovered rapidly.
MORTALITY: Further bleaching in 2002 that killed many of the remaining non-massive corals.
RECOVERY: The massive corals also bleached, but most recovered rapidly.
RB_SOURCE: Coral Bleaching and Mortality - the 1998 Event 4 Years Later and Bleaching to 2002. In: C.R. Wilkinson (ed.), Status of coral reefs of the world:2002. GCRMN Report, Australian Institute of Marine Science, Townsville. Chapter 1, pp 33-44
